# Rule: docs/adr/NNNN-<slug>.md

A numbered ADR is a **product or architecture decision about a component or
a feature**. The full list of what counts as an ADR is in
`docs/adr/README.md` (TL;DR: new package, new wire frame, new state
machine, new persistence shape, new surface, new cost model, new
adoption-score formula — **not** tooling choices).

## Frontmatter (required)

```yaml
---
id: NNNN
title: <one line>
type: <component | feature | runtime | contract | history | governance>
status: proposed | accepted | superseded | deprecated
created: YYYY-MM-DD
supersedes: []
principles: [P-1, …]
jobs: [H-1, …]
---
```

`principles` and `jobs` only need values once those exist (`SPEC.md`,
`ROADMAP.md`); for PR 1 there is nothing to point at and both arrays are
empty arrays `[]`.

## Body sections (required, in this order)

1. `# ADR NNNN — <Title>`
2. `## Context`
3. `## Decision`
4. `## Consequences` (with `### Positive`, `### Negative`, `### Reversibility`)
5. `## Alternatives considered`
6. `## Open questions`
7. `## Traceability`

## Numbering

- Four digits, zero-padded: `0001`, `0002`, … .
- Slug is kebab-case, lowercase, ASCII, derived from the title.
- Each new ADR gets the next available number; PR review may bump the
  number if a lower number is reserved by a concurrent PR.
- A superseded ADR is **not** renamed — its file stays; the `status:`
  flips, and the `supersedes:` field of the new ADR points at it.
